title: href attributes emptied when tag is disabled
body:
Not merge ready due to lack of tests & docs; filing for opinions. Probably not the right way to do this, so suggestions appreciated.

When a `<button>` is set as `disabled`, clicking it doesn't trigger any event listeners. However, applying `disabled` to an `<a>` tag doesn't have the same effect as the browser follows a `href` regardless of the rest of the attributes.

This PR extends the boolean attribute directives to add a list of change listeners, and `ng-href` uses this to remove the `href` attribute when the element becomes disabled.

title: feat(ngMock): decorator that adds Scope#$countChildScopes and Scope#$countWatchers
body:
When writing tests it's often useful to check the number of child scopes
or watchers within the current current scope subtree. Common use-case for advanced
directives is to test that the directive is properly cleaning up after itself. These
new methods simplify writing assertions that verify that child scopes were properly
destroyed or that watchers were deregistered.

title: fix($http): won't parse single space response
body:
According to [this question](http://stackoverflow.com/questions/3351247/how-to-return-truly-empty-body-in-rails-i-e-content-length-0), Rails in order to patch a bug in Safari, returns a single space when calling `head :ok`, which is the standard for POST requests.

Angular since [9ba24c54d](https://github.com/angular/angular.js/commit/9ba24c54d60e643b1450cc5cfa8f990bd524c130) checks if the body is empty before calling JSON parse, but this still breaks in this case, since the body isn't empty, but contains a single space. 

We are hitting this issue when trying to upgrade from Angular 1.2.10. This PR should help in that case.

title: wip: fix(ngModel): don't update when neither validity nor modelValue changed
body:
This is in response to https://github.com/angular/angular.js/issues/9063.

> don't update when neither validity nor modelValue changed

is what it actually does in the code, but is written to do that:

 > don't fire ngChange when an input with ngRequired is initially invalid, but its model is defined.

A better fix would require to find out why `required` fires the observer only once, but `ng-required`fires it twice, see https://github.com/angular/angular.js/issues/9063#issuecomment-59990139

title: fix(ngPattern): match behaviour of native HTML pattern attribute
body:
From https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/forms.html#attr-input-pattern

> The compiled pattern regular expression, when matched against a string, must have its start
anchored to the start of the string and its end anchored to the end of the string.

/CC @matsko please review

Closes #9881

title: feat($log): add $log.snapshot() option to make angular.copy of console l...
body:
...og arguments

makes angular.copy of object before logging so mutating objects are still recorded accurately in log
(improves default behavior of browser log which otherwise contains live object references that
can provide misleading picture of complex objects that change after being logged).
$log.snapshot() is sugar method for $log.snapshot.log() Also can call $log.snapshot.warn(), $log.snapshot.info(), $log.snapshot.error(), $log.snapshot.debug()
